SIMPLE: soften
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Soften
<hw>Sof"ten</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Softened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Softening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make soft or more
soft.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>To render less hard; -- said of matter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their arrow's point they <qex>soften</qex> in the flame.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>To mollify; to make less fierce or
intractable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Diffidence conciliates the proud, and <qex>softens</qex> the
severe.</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>To palliate; to represent as less enormous; <as>as,
to <ex>soften</ex> a fault</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>To compose; to mitigate; to assuage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Music can <qex>soften</qex> pain to ease.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> To make calm and placid.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All that cheers or <qex>softens</qex> life.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(f)</sd> <def>To make less harsh, less rude, less offensive, or
less violent, or to render of an opposite quality.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He bore his great commision in his look,⟦br⟧
But tempered awe, and <qex>softened</qex> all he spoke.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(g)</sd> <def>To make less glaring; to tone down; <as>as, to
<ex>soften</ex> the coloring of a picture</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(h)</sd> <def>To make tender; to make effeminate; to enervate;
<as>as, troops <ex>softened</ex> by luxury</as>.</def> <-- weaken
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(i)</sd> <def>To make less harsh or grating, or of a quality the
opposite; <as>as, to <ex>soften</ex> the voice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Soften</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Soften
<hw>Sof"ten</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become soft or softened, or
less rude, harsh, severe, or obdurate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Softener</ent>⟦br⟧
